<span id="freeTextContainer2414410345500873101">This was one of the formative books of my legal life, and with some relief I can report that it holds up well to a much later second read. Read it to be shocked by how closely morality was (and is) policed in Australia and the UK, and by the call to arms we should all feel about the inhumanity of the death penalty throughout the world. It feels like we should have come further, and gave me a sense of an opportunity our world has so far missed in giving all people access to human rights and a pla</span>
  <span id="freeText2414410345500873101" style="display:none">This was one of the formative books of my legal life, and with some relief I can report that it holds up well to a much later second read. Read it to be shocked by how closely morality was (and is) policed in Australia and the UK, and by the call to arms we should all feel about the inhumanity of the death penalty throughout the world. It feels like we should have come further, and gave me a sense of an opportunity our world has so far missed in giving all people access to human rights and a place to have them upheld. </span>
